description:
drh added on 2016-07-26 03:31:08:
In the following SQL, the same query is run twice, once before and once after
a CREATE INDEX.  This is clearly a bug since a CREATE INDEX should never 
change the answer, only make the answer appear more quickly.  The fact that
the index and the query are both a bit goofy should not matter.
CREATE TABLE t1(a INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, b INTEGER);
INSERT INTO t1(a,b) VALUES(500,123);
SELECT min(a) FROM t1 WHERE b='123' AND a>'456';
CREATE INDEX t1ba ON t1(b, a);
SELECT min(a) FROM t1 WHERE b='123' AND a>'456';
A quick initial assessment of this problem suggests that it is a bug in the
min/max optimization.
drh added on 2016-07-26 04:21:32:
The index need not by goofy.  The following is another example of the
failures that omits the PRIMARY KEY constraint:
CREATE TABLE t1(a INTEGER, b INTEGER);
INSERT INTO t1(a,b) VALUES(500,123),(600,123);
SELECT min(a) FROM t1 WHERE b='123' AND a>'456';
CREATE INDEX t1ba ON t1(b, a);
SELECT min(a) FROM t1 WHERE b='123' AND a>'456';
The use of the min() operator is required to generate the error however.
The problem is in the logic that skips initial NULL entries on the column
that is the argument to min().
